Simulations

Optimal signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) is not only achieved

at different flip angles for different modes but also

depends on relaxation times (see Fig. 1b,c). We aim at

finding optimal flip angle settings for TESS-based relax-

ometry and analyze the impact of noise on the T1 and T2 calculation. To this end, a Monte-Carlo simulation is

performed for a range of idealized homogeneous T2/T1probes with signal amplitudes according to Eqs. [1–5].

Optimal flip angle settings are explored based on

100,000 F1,0,À1 drawings with mean zero and 0.001M0 standard deviation. The value of the standard deviation

directly relates to the amount of noise in the acquired

MR images. From the sample of noisy signal amplitudes,

distributions of T1,2 with mean <T1,2> and standard deviation DT1,2 are calculated based on Eqs. [6–8]. The SNR for relaxation time mapping using TESS can then

be estimated from SNR T1;T2 :¼ <T1,2>/DT1,2. Relative

SNR is evaluated max{SNR T1 ,SNR T2

according to rSNR T1;T2 } for flip angles ranging

